1.2 Is this data frame tidy? Why or why not? Make sure to use the three rules of tidy data to justify your answer. If you can, tell me the “tidy” form for this data, and in what situations we might prefer the “tidy” or “messy” form.

This data frame is not tidy, it is wide as there is more than one variable represented in the columns.

For the first column, the variety variable is tidy, the is one variable for the column (rule 1) and there is one value in each cell (rule 3).

But when we look at the rest of the columns the count and country, or rating and country are included in the headings meaning that there is more than one variable for each column. This violates rule 1 that every variable is a column. Meaning the data isn’t tidy.

The pivot_longer function could be used to make this data set tidy. The first four observations of the tidy data would look like this:

Variety Country Count Rating
Cabernet Sauvignon Chile 719 86
Cabernet Sauvignon France 31 84
Cabernet Sauvignon Italy 123 90
Cabernet Sauvignon Spain 47 86

The tidy form is the same data, in a different layout. Many packages in R (in the tidyverse) will only work with tidy data. A consistent, tidy data form allows us to have an underlying uniformity in the data which can make it much easier to work with (mainly when switching between different models you can change the type you are looking to analyse very quickly). In this case the tidy data is more easy to run functions in the tidyverse such as ggplot which make visualising the data consistent.

The downside of tidy data, as demonstrated in the table above is that it can make the data less compact and less storage efficient. A value that previously represented the score for a county in one cell now takes two with an extra row being required. The condensed ‘messy’ form allows the same amount of information to be conveyed without spreading it out. If only interested in the summary of the data (with more simple statistics) it may just be easier to keep it ‘messy’ as making the data tidy adds an additional step to the process which in some cases is unnecessary.

The messy form has efficiency advantages for simple statistics, the tidy form makes more complex functions more easy to work with.

2.1 Does this decision tree provide evidence that French wine is overpriced? Why or why not?

The decision tree is provided with variety, country, points and review sentiment variables to find what’s influencing the prices of wine. It finds that points and country are the variables most useful in separating wines into groups of similar prices.

It provides evidence that the French wines which score 92 points and above are more expensive than other countries of this score. For wines above this score, whether or not they are French is influential enough to almost double their price ($62 for non French wines vs $125 for French wines). This is unlikely to be a result of a small sample of French wines as within this >92 scoring group, there are 5 countries and French wines make up just under 1/5 of the data scoring above 92 (3/18). This therefore supports the theory that high scoring French wines are overpriced (wines of similar score (proxy for quality) being more expensive because they are French).

There is no evidence from the decision tree that wine prices for those which score lower than 92 points are influenced by whether or not its French. Within this (lower scoring) branch of the tree, the only factor influencing the grouping of prices is another score split. Therefore the tree is unable to provide evidence towards lower scoring french wines being overpriced (more expensive for the same quality).

The decision tree lacks the ability to include factors it hasn’t seen. For example, how long a wine has aged for which may have an influence on the price charged for wine as the cost of producing it will be higher but it may not be met by an increase in quality (points scored). If French wines are more expensive to produce, due to being aged longer than other wines, while not having an increase in quality, this may be one explanation for the price discrepancy between french and other wines of similar quality. It would be expected however for this influence to make French wines ‘better’ or worth a higher price to be included in their score of quality. The decision tree is providing evidence for French wine being overpriced from the variables it has seen, but it is not able to account for other potential variables.

The decision tree finds that country and score are the key factors defining price. Generally, whether or not a wine is French is only influential on price when it scores highly. When French wines are compared to other wines of similar high quality (scoring above 92), they are nearly twice the price demonstrating they are more expensive at similar qualities and thus are overpriced.

2.2 Fit a linear model using points, country, and review_sentiment to predict price of a wine. What does this model tell you about the relationship between price and its predictors? Which predictors are significant? Which predictors are practically important?

vi_permute(
  object = lm_1,

  train = wines, 
  metric="rsq",
  nsim = 10,
  pred_wrapper = predict)

## 3 review_sentiment     0.0156 0.000507

The linear model fits a linear relationship between the variables and price. The model finds that all of the variables are statistically significant in their influence on price to a 99.9% confidence interval.

Generally, as the wine scores higher it prices higher. This initial linear model predicts that for each point increase in score of a wine, its price will rise by $5.38

It finds that relative to Chilean wine, all other countries have a higher price. If the wine is French rather than Chilean is expected cost $22.63 more. This is a larger difference than the rest of the countries; for Italy its $8.99, for Spain $7.64 and for the US $7.61 (each as an expected price increase relative to Chile).

Review sentiment is also influential on the price. If a wine scores 1 unit of review sentiment higher its price is expected to decrease by $6.80. This seems odd. We would expect a more favorable review to be linked to a more expensive wine but that may just expose one of the limitations of this initial model.

Variable importance shows when a variable is removed from a linear model, how influential that variable was on the R squared of that model. It ranks points as being the most important variable in the price of a wine (The link between higher scoring wine and higher prices is the strongest of all variables). The variable importance function finds that points (0.25) are more than 6 times as important than country (0.04) and that country is 4 times as important as review sentiment (0.02). These numbers are relative to each other (the interpretation comes from comparison), but the p values all being below 0.05 suggests that these results are statistically significant (the differences in importance are mathematically justified).

The linear model finds score is the key factor in the price of a wine, followed by the country: higher scoring wines are more expensive. The linear model also finds that French wines are the most expensive.

When assessing this initial models overall ability at predicting price this plot shows that the model is under predicting the price of nearly all wines. Wines below around $75 the model is close but is slightly over predicting. For wines which the model predicts will cost about $70 - $80, the observed value is significantly higher.

After around $100 observed price of wines they are very heavily under predicted as the model expects the wines to be significantly cheaper than they are. The red line shows the predictions of price (by the lm) relative to the observational price. The black line highlights the trend within the residuals of this this demonstrates some very strong bias in the data, as most prices are under predicted.

library(caret)
library(yardstick)

set.seed(2023)
wine_train= wines |> slice_sample(prop=0.75)
wine_test= wines |> filter(!description %in% wine_train$description)

lm_1_train= lm(price~ points + country + review_sentiment, data=wine_train)

pred_train_1= predict(lm_1_train)
pred_test_1=predict(lm_1_train, newdata= wine_test)

resid_train= residuals(lm_1_train)
resid_test= wine_test$price - pred_test_1



# comparing to the improved model 
lm_2_train= lm(price~ country*points + variety , data= wine_train)

pred_train_2= predict(lm_2_train)
pred_test_2=predict(lm_2_train, newdata= wine_test)

resid_train_2= residuals(lm_2_train)
resid_test_2= wine_test$price - pred_test_2

The predictive ability of the linear model is improved by including the interaction effect of country and points. This indicates that the interaction between these two variables is important in the price of wine. A high scoring french wine is likely to be a lot more expensive than a low scoring Chilean one.

In sample error indicates how well the model is able to fit to data it has seen. The improved model is $2.60 more accurate for the random seed I have chosen.

The out of sample error shows how general the model is, and demonstrates the predictive strength for data it hasn’t seen. As expected, the error is higher than the data it has seen but there is not a massive difference between the two suggesting that neither model is over fit. The improved model is $1.60 better at predicting prices for data it hasn’t seen for the specific split tested.

Comparing residuals

residuals_lm <- residuals(lm_1)
residuals_imp_lm <- residuals(Imp_lm)

comparison_data <- data.frame(
  Points = wines$points,  # Replace with your independent variable
  Residuals_lm = residuals_lm,
  Residuals_imp_lm = residuals_imp_lm
)

comparison_data$Residual_Difference = comparison_data$Residuals_lm - comparison_data$Residuals_imp_lm
mean_residual_difference <- mean(comparison_data$Residual_Difference)



comparison_data$Mean_Residuals = (comparison_data$Residuals_lm + comparison_data$Residuals_imp_lm) / 2
ggplot(comparison_data, aes(x = Mean_Residuals, y = Residual_Difference)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Bland-Altman Plot for Model Residuals",
       x = "Average of Residuals",
       y = "Difference in Residuals ( lm- Imp_lm)")

The Bland-Altman Plot allows us to compare the difference in residuals between the initial linear model and the improved model. The x axis shows the average of the residuals and the y axis indicates which model has smaller residuals. Points above the zero line are points where the residuals for the improved model are smaller, and between is where the initial model is smaller.

It appears that generally the residuals for the improved model are smaller as there are more points above the line than below it. This means that the difference between the predicted and the observed price is genrally lower for the improved model and thus it is an improvement.

labs(title= "Improved model residuals by country",x="Country", y="Residual (Test)")

When comparing the model residuals between the improved and initial model by country, (specifically for the testing set of data neither model has seen), generally the improved model under predicts the price slightly less. The stretched nature of France in the improved models residuals shows that there is greater variability in the residuals. This is indicative that the model is better than the initial one for predicting all countries apart from France. This provides more evidence that the price of French wine is not driven by purely the variables the models have seen and instead there is something else influencing it. This is more evidence that French wine is overpriced.

The root mean squared error is lower for both the in and out of sample error in the improved model. This model accounts for the interaction between scores and country which improves its predictive accuracy.

The improved model does a better job at predicting the prices of wines for all countries other than for France, indicating that something other than the variables provided is influencing the price of French wine.

3.1 From first principles (that is, without fitting a model or considering residuals), which of the two models is likely to perform better on this data set to predict the price of wines? Why do you think this will work better than the alternative? K-nn or random forest?

A random forest model will work better in this situation as the relationship between the variables and price is non linear (linear models are struggling with under prediction bias), there is a strong bias where price is consistently under predicted. Additionally K nn models may struggle with the curse of dimensionality because there are lots of dimensions.

One main issue with K nn models is that when there is a tie in the data, there is no way of differentiating which of the tie should be used, when there are categorical variables (in this case we have country and variety), there are lots of ties in the data, reducing the power of distance based prediction.

Another issue with K nn models is the curse of dimensionality, it stipulates that as there are more dimensions (variables) the meaning of distance deteriorates. 5 variables is getting close to the limit. Additionally, all distances are considered equally as important, this means scaling is required. This isn’t ideal for our wines data as we have already worked out that points are 6 times as important as country, and country is much more important than review sentiment in the price of the wine.

Regression forests are very powerful tools that can account for non linear relationships and interactions between features, and it is more robust to over fitting than K nn. Therefore as long as its not too computationally expensive the regression forest will be the better model for this situation.

The data set has two measures of quality, points and review_sentiment. I have chosen to use points as the measure of quality as the linear model and random forests found a much weaker influence on price from review sentiment.

Generally, higher scoring French wines are more expensive than wines from other countries of similar scores. This implies that high quality french wines are overpriced.

The threshold is around 92 where the prices become noticeably higher for French wines when compared to other non French wines. This is seen across all of the models (linear, knn and decision trees). Below this threshold, the prices of French wines compared to wines of similar quality are not noticeably different, meaning that the French wines are not overpriced when they are of lower quality.

For example, when comparing a selection of wines which score between 91 and 95 points, a French one is expected to cost $95.25, while a wine from all other countries would be $54.53. This is substantial evidence to show that French wines are overpriced. The second bar plots show that as wines get higher points, the difference in price between French an other wines becomes more clear. Therefore the French wines are more overpriced, the higher quality they are.
